/wiki/Akaa: Akaa (Swedish: Ackas) is a town and a municipality in Pirkanmaa, Finland. It was created on January 1, 2007 when the town of Toijala and the municipality of Viiala were united into a single town. The municipality of Kylmäkoski was consolidated with Akaa on 1 January 2011.
/wiki/Hauho: Hauho is a former municipality of Finland. It was situated in the province of Southern Finland and is today a part of the region of Tavastia Proper (Kanta-Häme / Egentliga Tavastland).
/wiki/H%C3%A4meenlinna: Hämeenlinna (Swedish: Tavastehus; Karelian: Hämienlinna) is a city and municipality of about 68,000 inhabitants in the heart of the historical province of Häme in the south of Finland. Hämeenlinna is the oldest inland city of Finland and was one of the most important Finnish cities until the 19th century. It still remains an important regional center.
/wiki/Hollola: Hollola is a municipality of Finland, located in the Päijänne Tavastia region.  The municipality is unilingually Finnish and has a population of 23,570 (31 January 2019) and covers an area of 727.47 square kilometres (280.88 sq mi) of which 68.66 km2 (26.51 sq mi) is water. The population density is 50.89 inhabitants per square kilometre (131.8/sq mi).
/wiki/Holy_Cross_Church,_Hattula: The Holy Cross Church (Finnish: Pyhän Ristin kirkko) in Hattula, Finland, is the oldest church in the former Tavastia (Häme) province.
/wiki/Hattula: Hattula is a municipality of Finland. Its seat is in Parola.
/wiki/Koski_Hl: Hämeenkoski (Finnish pronunciation: [ˈhæmeːŋˌkoski]; Koski Hl until 1995, see Koski Tl) is a former municipality of Finland. It was merged to the municipality of Hollola on 1 January 2016.
/wiki/H%C3%A4meenkoski: Hämeenkoski (Finnish pronunciation: [ˈhæmeːŋˌkoski]; Koski Hl until 1995, see Koski Tl) is a former municipality of Finland. It was merged to the municipality of Hollola on 1 January 2016.
/wiki/Janakkala: Janakkala is a municipality of Finland. Its administrative centre is in Turenki, which is often erroneously shown on maps as being "Janakkala".
/wiki/Kalvola: Kalvola is a former municipality of Finland. Its seat was in Iittala. It was consolidated with Hämeenlinna on 2009-01-01.
/wiki/Lammi_Church: Lammi Church is a medieval stone church located in Lammi, Hämeenlinna, Southern Finland. It was built during the 1510s.
/wiki/Lammi: Lammi (Swedish: Lammi, also Lampis) is a former municipality of Finland. It was consolidated with Hämeenlinna on 2009-01-01.
/wiki/Padasjoki: Padasjoki is a municipality of Finland.
/wiki/Renko: Renko is a former municipality of Finland. It was consolidated with Hämeenlinna on 2009-01-01.
/wiki/Somero: Somero (Finnish pronunciation: [ˈsomero]) is a municipality of Finland, located in the province of Western Finland and part of the Southwest Finland region. The municipality has a population of 8,827 (31 January 2019) and covers an area of 697.67 square kilometres (269.37 sq mi) of which 29.9 km2 (11.5 sq mi) is water. The population density is 13.22 inhabitants per square kilometre (34.2/sq mi). Somero is unilingually Finnish.
/wiki/P%C3%A4lk%C3%A4ne: Pälkäne is a municipality of Finland.

/wiki/S%C3%A4%C3%A4ksm%C3%A4ki: Sääksmäki is a village and a former municipality, currently part of Valkeakoski in the Pirkanmaa region of Western Finland. A past president of Finland, Pehr Evind Svinhufvud, the Finnish film producer and director Veikko Aaltonen, eminent Finnish historian Eino Jutikkala, and actress Pirkko Mannola, were born there.
/wiki/Valkeakoski: Valkeakoski (lit. white rapids) is a small city and municipality in Finland.
/wiki/Tammela,_Finland: Tammela is a municipality of Finland. The first mention of a village named Tammela was in documents from 1423.
/wiki/Tuulos: Tuulos (Swedish: Tuulos, also Tulois) is a former municipality of Finland. It was consolidated with Hämeenlinna on January 1, 2009. The administrative center of Tuulos was Syrjäntaka.
/wiki/Urjala: Urjala (Swedish: Urjala, also Urdiala)  is a municipality of Finland.
/wiki/Vanaja_(Finland): Vanaja is a former municipality of Finland. It was located in Tavastia Proper about 100 kilometres (60 mi) north of Helsinki. It is also speculated that it might have been the name for an Iron Age and early Middle Ages settlement found opposite to the Häme Castle.
/wiki/List_of_medieval_stone_churches_in: This is a list of medieval stone churches in Finland. A total number of 104 fieldstone churches were built between the 13th and 16th century, of which 83 have been preserved. Numbers include the sacristies of uncompleted churches as well as three churches in Vyborg which is now part of Russia.
